title: For Sale:  Steyr 1886 Kropatschek Infantry Rifle EXC+ Bore SUPER Clean READY 2 SHOOT
postcontent: This is a standard Kropatschek Infantry rifle with an outstanding bore in perfect shooting condition. This is a regular infantry rifle (longer barrel) but compared to many up for auction recently (Invaluable and other auction services) it is super clean with an EXC+ bore. It has also been disassembled, cleaned and checked over. The last black-powder cartridge rifle designed and these were plenty strong to handle the conversion to smokeless powder. If unfamiliar with Krops, drop me a message or check You Tube (a couple of excellent videos).  The elevator mechanism is smooth and slick as is the bolt. Most of the Krops have a well-used exterior as they were in use from 1886 until the 1970s in parts of the world. The barrel on this one is still darker and has not faded to gray like many. The bluing has turned a slight brown tone with the finish darker and nicer towards the receiver and like 80+ % of them, there is roughness at the wood line (only visible removed from stock) but no active corrosion. This one has been disassembled and cleaned including the magazine tube which gleams like new inside. The bolt was totally taken apart and a century of grime and grease came out. The trigger went from gummy to crisp. The inside of the stock still has cosmoline but it is fine where it is so I left it. VERY nice trigger on this one. The receiver has very nice dark bluing in excellent condition and the metal is overall better than the wood though the wood is solid as a rock with no cracks. The cartouche is very visible on both sides. The wood has been around 130 years and in countless countries and possibly several wars and battles. This one, like most, has a non matching bolt number to the rifle but the rest of the rifle matches. The bolt parts are all matching except the bolt head. Every screw present (some listed are missing some) and all screws and threads have been cleaned. These are LONG rifles and superb shooters. This one is a shooter and not a museum piece and will make an excellent example for a collection. Modern ammo is available on GB and there is still 1920s ammo available (I have some) but using modern loads with cast bullets and moderate powder is a very easy to shoot combo and doesnt stress the gun at all. I have watched these double in price over 2 to 3 years and they can only go up as you never see antique guns go down in value. There are still many in Portugal, who ordered all Krops made (1886 is the only year) and they are popular in South Africa and Australia (where they sell for 2 to 3 times the US price)as well. If you want a solid Krop with no surprises that needs NOTHING but ammo to shoot and shoot well, this is it. You wont need to clean it or worry about any of the parts not working when you get it. You dont need to hunt down any screws or parts, and you do not need to repair the stock. The gorgeous bore means it will shoot like a champ, as well as it did when made. There are some in better overall (wood) cosmetic condition that CAN turn up if you wait, but based on the prices I have seen them go for, this a great buy. Ships for $42 as it is a big boy. As an antique, no FFL necessary but a copy of state ID is to ship. Paypal must use SEND MONEY TO FRIENDS AND FAMILY TO AVOID FEESOVER 25 MORE PHOTOS AVAILABLE

title: For Sale:  "MEDICINE GUN" WINCHESTER 1895 .405 TAKEDOWN - NR circa 1913, MINTY BORE, Lyman Windage, 1886, 1894
postcontent: On a true "NO RESERVE" $0.01 start auction I have a very desirable Winchester Model 1895 Takedown sporting rifle chambered in the most sought after 405 caliber. This rifle, serial #81870 was manufactured in 1913. The gun comes with a special order Takedown feature, factory sling swivels and I believe a factory installed Lyman receiver sight with windage adjustment. The .405 was introduced in 1904. It remains to this day the most powerful rimmed cartridge designed for lever-action rifles, the only modern lever action cartridge that approaches its performance is the .450 Marlin. President Theodore Roosevelt had to not one, not two, but three 1895's in .405 and it proved very effective on almost every sort of game in Africa. The big 300 grain bullet was a hard hitter with initial muzzle velocity of more than 2230 fps. In perhaps the best presidential endorsement of any product ever, Roosevelt wrote in Scribers Magazine "The Winchester .405 is, at least for me personally the medicine gun for lions!" The .405 was discontinued in 1932. As for condition the receiver retains most of its toning original blue finish. The original 24" tapered round barrel retains 95% of its original bluing. The original walnut stocks are in very good condition, retaining some of their original oil finish, with minimal handling marks. A period correct NOSHOC recoil pad has been added to the buttstock, appearing to have always been there (believe me if you are going to shoot this rifle you'll be glad its there). The action is tight and smooth, mechanically perfect. The bore is MINTY, showing a mirror shine with sharp rifling. I would rate it at 95%+. The barrel address and caliber markings are perfect. The screws are very good and most remain unturned. The special order Lyman receiver with a windage adjustment is marked "95". The Takedown mechanism locks up tight. In all this old gun still retains a lot of condition, with an excellent bore that would make this rifle a great addition to ones collection and/or a perfect vintage hunting rifle. I have provided over 90 photos and offer a 3 day inspection period so you can bid with confidence. All pictures were taken outdoors in natural light and provide an accurate depiction of its condition. I will need a signed FFL of C&R to ship. Insurance is included with shipping. Thank you for looking.
